 Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Genève","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  Altered spelling of northern French Denef(v)e, a habitational name, with the preposition <i>de</i>, for someone from places called Neffe in the Belgian provinces of Namur and Luxembourg.","2  Dutch (de Neve): kinship name from Middle Dutch <i>neve</i> ‘grandson’, ‘(male) cousin’, ‘nephew’ + the definite article <i>de</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gérold","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>wald</i> ‘rule’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. There has been some confusion with   Gerard .  It died out in England at the end of the 13th century. However, it continued to be popular in Ireland, where it had been brought in the 12th century at the time of Strongbow's invasion. It was used in England in the 17th century and revived in the 19th century, along with several other long-extinct names of Norman, Old English, and Celtic origin, and is now more common than <i>Gerard</i>, which survived all along as an English ‘gentry’ name."],"variants":[{"name":"Jerrold","meanings":["Rare variant of   Gerald  , probably a transferred use of the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1353604,"age":276,"year":"1291","julianDay":2192589,"description":"Three valleys in Central Switzerland unite against the counts of Habsburg and fight for autonomy. Cities join the confederacy. They conquer territories in northern and southern Switzerland.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1353605,"age":300,"year":"1315","julianDay":2201354,"description":"Decisive Battle against the counts of Habsburg.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1353606,"age":484,"year":"1499","julianDay":2268559,"description":"Swiss forces defeated the forces of the Holy Roman Empire. Switzerland won its complete independence from the empire.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1353607,"age":521,"year":"1536","julianDay":2282072,"description":"Switzerland is a loose confederacy of 13 cities and small valley communities dominating the rest of the country. A few families control state affairs. Several rebellions put down by military force: repressed aspects of history in a country so proud of it's tradition of democracy.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1353608,"age":633,"year":"1648","julianDay":2322980,"description":"All European peace treaty formally accepts Switzerland as an independent nation.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1353609,"age":783,"year":"1798","julianDay":2377767,"description":"Revolution in Switzerland. Farmers in occupied territories become free citizens. Centralistic parliamentary republic according to French model. Occupation by French troops and some battles of Napoleon vs. Austria and Russia in Switzerland.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Gérold II de Genève was born about 1015, in Geneva, Geneva, Switzerland, his father, Gérold Ier de Genève, was 26 and his mother, Berthe de Flandre, was 55. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Gisèle de Bourgogne. He died before 1800, in his hometown."},"et":{"um 1015–vor 1800":"umbes 1015–enne 1800","1015–1800":"1015–1800","1020–10